erovskite LaCoO<inf>3</inf>. Results of cleavage energies indicate that the propensity to reconstruct depends on the orientation of terminations. The stability of the reconstructed termination relates to the nominal charge of a given surface. O atoms on surfaces interact repulsively with each other. We discuss the thermodynamic stabilities of all terminations using the Grand potential. A stability diagram demonstrates that the ground termination is LaO-(001) p(1 × 1) surface in most cases, while it transforms to the LaO <inf>3</inf>-(111) p(1 × 1) surface in O-rich/La-poor condition. The results provide potential candidates for future studies of LaCoO<inf>3</inf> surface catalysis. © 2013 Elsevier B.V.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84887995382" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84887995382&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84887995382%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60021508" id="60021508"><affilname>University of Notre Dame</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60025778" id="60025778"><affilname>University Michigan Ann Arbor</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60000501" id="60000501"><affilname>General Motors</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="55872571200" seq="1"><ce:initials>Z.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Chen Z.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Chen</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Zhengzheng</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>Z.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Chen Z.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Chen</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Zhengzheng</ce:given-name></preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/55872571200<